18: RESPONSE: Thank you for providing such clear guidance regarding the next round of review. We have carefully addressed each of the points you raise here. Detailed responses appear in the point-by-point replies to reviewers below, but to summarize:
19: We have updated the references Reviewer 1 flagged as dated. Our introduction now provides more contemporary citations (e.g., to Locke and Latham (2019), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), Andor, Gerster, and Peters (2020), Henry, Ferraro, and Kontoleon (2019), and Mertens and Schultz (2021)); the General Discussion does the same, incorporating more recent work alongside the foundational citations we retain (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007)
20: Relatedly, we have expanded the introduction’s theoretical framing (pp. X-X) to articulate why descriptive feedback alone is sufficient to change selection decisions pertaining to women and underrepresented minorities. Consistent with the broader logic of the feedback literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. However, we now make clear that descriptive feedback can also be effective without a paired goal in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched. This is the case for the types of diversity-related selection decisions we study in our paper, where injunctive norms against prejudicial behavior are sustained by both internal egalitarian commitments and external legal, organizational, and social pressures.
21: We have revised the Introduction (pp. X) and Discussion to acknowledge the shifting socio-political landscape around organizational commitments to DEI in the United States flagged by Reviewer 2. We situate our work within two parallel developments. In the U.S., explicit DEI rhetoric has retreated since 2024. In addition, international governments have moved in the opposite direction, passing laws that require firms to disclose or correct gender disparities in pay and leadership. Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act of 2023 mandates public disclosure of firm-level gender representation and pay gaps (Ressia, 2024). The EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires transposition across member states by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024). The EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% gender minimum on listed-company boards. We argue that these shifts reinforce the contemporary value of our research even against an ever-changing sociopolitical backdrop, with a recent decline in support for corporate diversity policies specifically in the United States.
22: We have provided a more tightly bounded theoretical discussion of the scope of our intervention, in line with Reviewer 2’s request. We agree that motivation to respond without prejudice is central to our account of increasing selections of women and racial minorities. However, we also discuss how the organizational climate around DEI is merely one part of the external motivation to respond without prejudice pathway that can influence individuals when it comes to promoting women and racial minorities. Specifically, the external motivation to control prejudice pathway also encompasses the fact that selection decisions are generally observable by colleagues, prospective candidates, and outside stakeholders, and the implicit norm against appearing prejudiced operates well beyond any one firm’s stated commitments. While organizations’ explicit DEI commitments are themselves often responses to external stakeholder, legal, and political pressures rather than the source of internal organizational norms (Levi & Fried, 2024), a given firm’s retreat from DEI rhetoric reflects shifting external pressure on the firm, not the disappearance of broader social pressure on individual selection decisions. We also now discuss how the internal motivation to respond without prejudice as well as selectors’ personally-held egalitarian beliefs may not be as malleable in the face of changes in organizational climate, and our existing evidence for why people respond to feedback about the race and gender of their past selectees (see Study 4) is, if anything, more readily explained by internal rather than external motives. In summary, we expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to be somewhat attenuated in fully private/anonymous selection decisions or in contexts that explicitly encourage discriminatory behavior.
23: I have two remaining requests, one about style and one about analysis.  Although the paper is generally well-written and the studies are well-designed, I found reading the paper a bit of a slog.  Some of that is that much of the analysis was nearly identical across studies, and the repetitive style of reporting made the paper feel bulky.  I understand that my tastes for writing and streamlining might be idiosyncratic, but I wonder if there can be streamlining (as in Figure 2) in which some of the repeated analysis (like comparison between the theoretically targeted feedback and the “control” feedback) shows up in a Table with the relevant statistics.  I won’t make this a requirement, but I’d like the authors to take this feedback (no pun intended) seriously and consider whether there is something that can be done.  I will also add that the paper right now is close to the page limit since you have moved the figures and tables out of the main text (“All invited revisions must adhere to the following page limit: 47 pages with 25 lines of text per page (double spacing) or 32 pages with 33 lines of text per page (1.5 spacing). An online appendix will not count toward the page limit.” https://pubsonline.informs.org/page/mnsc/submission-guidelines)
24: RESPONSE: We thank you for this feedback and agree that the prior version’s repeated presentation of the same comparisons made the empirical sections longer than warranted. The revised manuscript is now [X] pages and reflects a substantial streamlining of the Methods and Results sections, particularly for later studies to avoid unnecessary repetition/redundancy. To that end, and following your guidance, we have introduced a new consolidated, cross-study table (Table 2) summarizing the secondary comparisons of the relative effects of feedback about race/gender vs. other attributes in a centralized location. Moreover, we relegated the reporting of the regression specifications behind those comparisons to a dedicated section of the Appendix, with explicit references from each Results section.
25: I think that Study 4b goes a long way in terms of convincing me that there is something special about gender/racial etc representational feedback relative to feedback on other attributes.  One though and one request.  Although I think that the package of studies is very compelling, I still found myself wishing that you had tested whether the alternative descriptive feedback that you shared was on par with gender in terms of importance.  My intuition, for example, in Study 1 is that “(1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university” would be seen as less important than gender.  Two suggestions -- you could get a separate group and “post-test” some of these items and if they are as important or nearly as important report that.  If on the other hand, they are a lot less important, I would ask you to consider running Study 1 again so that the paper starts with a strong study.
26: RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and incorporated the result into the Discussion of Study 1 (p. X). We recruited N = 300 Prolific participants and randomly assigned each to rate, on a 1 to 7 importance scale, one of the four expert-attribute statements used in Study 1’s feedback manipulation, with the NPR producer framing held constant. Two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than the gender attribute (“were women”; M = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76): “worked at a university” (M = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = −3.76, p < .001, d = −0.61) and “were under 50 years old” (M = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = −2.81, p = .006, d = −0.46). The third, “based on the West Coast of the United States,” showed no significant difference in importance (M = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). Differences in perceived importance therefore cannot account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections in Study 1, consistent with our claim that descriptive feedback motivates behavior on dimensions carrying an implicit injunctive norm.
27: On the request, I liked Study 4b and think that it does a good job of showing that feedback about gender is different than feedback about other important dimensions.  In addition, your studies show that gender/race feedback lead subjects to adjust their portfolios about the base rate.  That said, I’m still left wondering whether your findings are showing what you say or it is just that people use these other measures appropriately in their initial selections.  I’d like you to at least discuss this possibility, and perhaps there is additional analysis that you can do to address this.
28: RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this alternative. We agree it is worth testing directly, and we report a follow-up analysis below (Table R1). We have also added a footnote to the Discussion of Study 4 (p. X) that summarizes this evidence and makes the underlying theoretical claim more explicit in the manuscript.
29: In our studies, we make no assumptions about the normative or “appropriate” level for any attribute in the absence of explicit goals or prescriptions. We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback, and only for race and gender. This fits the theoretical framing already in the paper: descriptive feedback shifts behavior on a given dimension only when that dimension carries an implicit injunctive norm that the feedback calls into question. We argue this holds for race and gender but not for the comparison attributes we test (see Introduction, p. X, and General Discussion, p. X).
30: That said, we can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an “appropriate” level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Whereas, feedback about other attributes increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
31: However, we acknowledge that the comparison side of this analysis is meaningfully underpowered, so we can only provide suggestive evidence of our claims. Moreover, we further recognize that zero is a useful but imperfect floor, since for some participants it may reflect a deliberate preference. For these reasons, we treat this analysis as imperfect but directional evidence against the alternative that participants are selecting comparison attributes at appropriate levels to begin with.
