diversity” between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to “belonging” (Paradigm, 2025).Together, Incorporating these developments also helped us sharpen why the paper’s central question remains important in the current climate. The paper’s contribution is not simply that descriptive feedback may serve as a useful managerial tool, but that descriptive feedback about past selection patterns can change subsequent decisions when those patterns raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to your own egalitarian standards. The recent pullback from explicit DEI rhetoric in U.S. organizations is therefore relevant to the scope of our theory. To the extent that corporate messaging and formal diversity commitments are one source of people’s motivation to respond without prejudice, their retreat may weaken that pathway. At the same time, these organizational cues are not the only source of such concerns. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individuals’ own egalitarian commitments can continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI language. Thus, the current landscape does not simply make the paper less timely; it helps clarify when descriptive feedback should be more or less likely to matter. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback as a light-touch approach: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals, it remains important to understand whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
